column13:
The support is brilliant, like the support is insanely good.

The thing with Privato is when you contact them they always get back to you within minutes doesn't matter if it's a Monday or Sunday they are always there as long as it's at a decent time.

But that's not what I find amazing about them, what I find amazing is how knowledgeable the support is, it's not just some clickfarm rented out to reply with a script, it's actual knowledgeable support who have access to see things and can tell you what's really going on.

I will be attempting to store my money with Privato for the fact that they don't ask for POI (proof of income) or anything like that, not necessarily because it's something non-legit but with my regular FIAT bank they requested that I get the ID of someone I was exchanging BTC with online before they can release their rightful money.

I'm very excited to be using you, thank you for such a good service :)

column13: "Privato Bank does not fit into a category that requires KYC documents, which make it impossible for 87% of people on earth to open a bank account. We accept everyone." Thank you thank you thank you! I'm glad that I'm not the only one who has been sounding alarm over this!! I've been raising this very issue with politicians, community leaders, and business leaders for years, only to get this incredulous look. The reality is that there is a massive "unbanked" and "unbankable" population in this world, even in "advanced" countries such as the USA (actually, they may be the worst). Now that Privato Bank is offering a real, workable solution. Now, I've already seen some slanderous posts online about Privato Bank. But ask yourself here: If Privato Bank is "illegal" -- that it is less than 100 percent confident about its legality per Panamanian laws -- why would it offer ACH, IBAN, PayPal, and so on for deposits and withdrawals? Because, as anyone can easily guess, those transactions can easily be traced back, and American companies such as PayPal do have to comply with AML anyway. If this is purely a case of a bad OpSec, then Privato would have already been shut down! As for some people slandering Privato for "unsophisticated websites": If one takes an honest look at how Privato Bank operates, one would immediately notice that there is NO single point of failure, unlike most major commercial banks' "online banking" portals! This is not a bug but it's a feature! Overreliance on automation and computer technologies is the reasons why we have a rampant identity theft and hacking problems! I'm tired of trolls who don't have an open mind for new innovations (though: numbered anonymous bank accounts are actually very old ideas, used to be very common in Switzerland, Germany, and Austria until the 20th century).  As Mahatma Gandhi said, "First they ignore you, then they laugh at you, then they fight you, then you win." So, Privato Bank, I am grateful for your initiatives and I pray for a great success! You're changing the world for the better.
column20: emily, your words are so very kind and honest.  Thank you for taking the time to clarify the importance of our vision and mission.  In the fight against world poverty, we've learned that the 88.5% of people who cannot have a traditional bank account have one thing in common: it is not gender, geography or luck; rather it is their government-mandated inability to access financial services.  Privato Bank and our affiliated financial service partner companies aim to reach these people so that all may have the opportunity to improve their quality of life.  This has driven us from the beginning and drives us through the relentless and pounding attacks.   "The worship of state is the worship of force.
